segments.text: Turn it off.
Do you have it off?
It's on now.
Turn it off?
Okay, if you could tell me a little bit about the difference between the old and new towns.
Just start with the old town, what it was like.
It's going to be hard for me to tell how the old town was, but it's 90% of the people that live in the old town, they were Latin Americans.
We had very few Anglo Americans.
And the old town is now underwater.
We had a big flood in, I think it was 1954.
And we moved just before that big flood in 1953 to this new town of Zapata.
The old town
Zapata was the old courthouse there.
It was built in 1900.
And now everything is underwater.
Everything's underwater.
Well, how did it happen to be underwater?
In 1954, a big flood came along the Rio Grande.
And we all had to move in a hurry.
Of course, we had here in these new towns, we had to move some of the old buildings from the old town to this new site here.
But you already expected to have to move.
Oh, yes.
We were advised by the International Boundary and Water Commission that the old town was going to be flooded.
since they were building that big dam, which is just, say, about two miles from the county line of Zapata.
The dam is in Stark County.
And we were advised by the boundary commission that in the first big flood, the town of Zapata would be flooded, that we had to move, and we had to move.
You mean when the flood came, it was very quick?
Yes, it was very quick.
How much time did you actually have?
Well, we had about, I'd say about three days.
Three days?
Yeah.
How come people hadn't moved sooner?
Well, I tell you, some people, not all, but some people, they thought that the old town would never be flooded.
Oh, really?
They didn't believe.
I'm not going to say that all, but some of the people, they didn't want to move.
They just waited until the last minute, I'll say.
Well, had there been any effort to save the town?
Yes, there were made effort, but not...
They were not... We were about...
They can save the town.
There were no way to save the town.
Now, did you get any kind of replacement for...
Yes, we were paid by the...
government, by the U.S. government, for our houses.
Before we go on, why don't you say your name in here and how long you've lived here?
Well, I lived here all my life.
I was born in the county, and I've been living here all my life, except for the
a few months out of it, but just working outside of the county.
But I've been living here in this county for all my life.
And your name is?
Juventino Martinez.
And so you remember both the old town and the new town very well.
Yes, yes.
Is life considerably different?
Well, not to us, not much different.
To me, I won't say to me, and I think to most of the people, it's just about the same.
We're just living in the people that used to go out north to work.
They still do the same.
They live here in the town.
And they'll go and stay about two or three months out of the county, and they'll just come back, and they have their homes here in Zapata.
What percentage of the people would you say do go work up north?
Well, it's not a very big percentage.
I'd say about, I don't think so, two or three percent.
Two or three, but that wouldn't be very many people.
No, no, no, not very many people.
So most people stay here all year?
They stay here all year, yes.
Well, has there been any... Would you say that there have been advantages in moving or disadvantages?
Well, I can tell you.
Some people, I think it was an advantage on account of this big lake.
Some people, they are doing good business because we have a lot of people coming from outside, a lot of tourists.
Most of it, every winter, they start coming in about, I say in about September and October.
The people come from North Michigan, New Mexico, Arizona, Ohio.
And I say the, sometimes the two, I say about 1,000 people or maybe more.
They stay about two, three months.
especially as retired people.
So this brings in some income that you get.
Yeah, it brings a lot of income.
But we lost, on account of building this dam, the county lost, I say, about 4,000 or 5,000 acres that were irrigation.
Well, that's a lot of land.
Yeah, a lot of land, yes.
I say about, I don't know, I say,
I want to say about from 2,000 to 3,000 acres.
Well, has it been possible to put another 2,000 or 3,000 acres back into irrigation?
I don't think so, ma'am.
We don't have, you know, the riverbed.
It was just level land.
It was beautiful land for irrigation.
Right.
We didn't have any trouble at all.
I didn't own any land, but the people that owned the land, they had a lot of good land for irrigation.
Now, since the...
Water covered all that land.
Now most of the out-country is now hilly country.
I see.
And what about the soil?
Well, the soil is very good.
But it would be very lot of trouble to level that land to irrigate.
Of course, we have on the north part of the county, I say from here, we got a lot of good land for irrigation too.
And we don't have the water now.
You don't have the water?
No, ma'am.
With all the water in your lake?
All the water in the lake belongs to the state or to the U.S. government.
And you have to get a permission, and sometimes they don't give you enough water.
Well, what about people who already had those lands under irrigation by then?
Well, some of those people, I think they lost their Their water rights?
Their water rights.
And there's not anything they can do?
I don't know.
Unless they go back to the state commission, water commission.
So this is one of the disadvantages.
Yes, ma'am.
The loss of both the flatlands and the water.
The water, yes.
The irrigation on those lands.
They used to raise a lot of tomatoes, onions, cotton, good cane, corn.
We don't have that anymore.
We have a little smaller irrigation from San Ignacio.
That's next town from here.
They have irrigation over there.
San Ignacio didn't have to move, did it?
No, they didn't have to move.
They tried to move that town too, but they finally decided that they didn't have to move.
Was this town a lot like San Ignacio before?
Yes.
Yes, well, more or less the same.
What about social life?
Going from farming to reliance on tourism, has that affected life here in any way?
Well, I don't know.
It didn't affect me much because I've only been working in the courthouse most of my time.
I used to work with the county clerk.
I'm still here with the county clerk.
You're with the county clerk?
No, I'm not working with him anymore.
I quit about four months ago.
I resigned.
I'm retired now.
Oh, you're retired.
I'm too old to work.
I still do a little work.
I don't want to just stay home and lay down.
I'd like to do something.
What about the young people?
Are they staying here now?
Well, they are staying here.
We have a very good high school, very good elementary schools.
And those buildings, they are very nice.
We didn't have those in the old town.
And with the help of the US government, the schools are in very good shape.
We have very good, I say, teachers, very good teachers.
Most of them, they have their degrees, master degrees.
Are they mostly people from here, or are they from other places?
Well, mostly from here, and just very few from outside.
Now, Guerrero, across the river, was also relocated, wasn't it?
Yeah, it was relocated.
That old town was built, I'd say, about 220 years ago.
It was an old Spanish town, built of sand rocks,
narrow streets.
And now they have a new modern town.

The difference between the government, the Mexican and the American government, that the Mexican government built their houses in the new Guerrero, and they were just given to those people, those people that moved to the new Guerrero.
So everybody got a new house.
Everybody got a new house.
All those that own houses in old Guerrero, they went and got one in the new Guerrero.
What about the people from Zapata?
We had to build our own.
We just got the money, and we had to build our own.
Which do you think was better?
Well, I don't know.
I think the money was better.
The money was there.
Of course, I don't know.
I don't know.
It's just a matter of thinking, really.
Maybe.
I really don't know.
Some of those people, they had very beautiful houses there.
The ones here?
No.
No, the ones over there?
Yes.
They got very beautiful houses?
Yes, some of them got beautiful brick houses.
Were they satisfied with their houses?
Some were satisfied and some were not.
That's the difference.
Over here, the same thing.
Some were satisfied with the money.
With the money, some were not satisfied.
So if you were going to say you were on a planning commission and you had to help the government decide what to do if a town was being moved because of a dam, what would you recommend?
Having seen it done two different ways.
Well, I tell you, I was working with the boundary commission at that time.
Oh, you were?
Yes.
I was employed by the boundary commission for that purposes.
I used to go house by house with the people, advising them that they had to move because the town of Zapata would be flooded.
And some people believed me, and some they said, no, you're crazy.
This town will never be flooded.
Although Zapata had actually been flooded twice, even without a dam, had been moved twice.
No, when it was moved twice, the oldest...
The oldest.
The oldest, it was named not Zapata, it was named Carrizo.
It was flooded.
And in 1900, moved to this, to a new site, which is now, we call it the old site now.
Then it's flooded again.
Yeah, it's flooded again.
And I hope we're not going to get flooded again here.
Because the tables had been moved once without a dam, and then we moved again.
Who were the first families that moved into Zapata?
I guess we moved most everybody at the same time.
Oh, oh, to New Zapata.
I was thinking about Carizo.
Well, I don't know much.
It goes back a long way.
Long ways back.
I don't know much about that.
Because in the old Carrizo, there were the Redmonds.
I don't remember.
But I think the Redmonds were the first to build the old Carrizo, Redmond.
And there were a lot of people.
I don't know who they were.
But then the news about that, everybody pretty much, you mean everybody waited until the flood of 54?
Almost.
Yes, just about.
And were there any houses here for people to live in?
Yes, there were some.
Who had built those?
No, no, we moved some of the old houses.
Oh, you moved some of the old houses?
And some people, especially from below here.
There was the Lo Pea Village and all those small villages below Zapata.
They were flooded before the old town Zapata, and those people didn't have houses.
The government lent those people tents.
They were living in tents.
Good heavens.
How long did they live in tents?
Well, some lived about two, three months.
Some lived four, five months, some six months.
And most of those people, they were the Red Cross.
Did a lot of good help to those people.
They were furnished with tents and with food.
for some time now.
How much warning did you have that you were going to have to move in the first place?
Well, we had long, many times we were warned.
No, many times.
Many times, yes.
It wasn't really unexpected.
And it was, I was instructed to tell the people that they have to be moved.
Say, no, we are not

They finally, when they saw that the old town of La Pena, which is about 18 miles below here, was flooded, then they start doing something to, because if we had a lot in the old town, they had this new town here, and they built the subdivision.
And we had to trade lots.
If I had a lot in the old town, they gave me a lot in the new town.
And I start doing that with the people.
I start trading lots with those people.
That was my duty at that time.
That was my work, the work I was doing.
Well, now, Mercurio Martinez Sr. from Laredo was also doing that, wasn't he?
Yes, he, Mercurio Martinez, myself, and we had another old man from Lo Peo that we all worked together.
Did you know Mercurio Martinez?
Oh, I knew him very well.
What kind of
He was a very nice person.
He was very well-educated.
Have you seen his book, The Kingdom of Zapata?
Yes, I've seen The Kingdom of Zapata.
I think my name's in that book.
I can't recall right now.
It had a lot of names, but I'll look back through it.
Maybe.
I'm not sure, but I think my name's in it.
I think it probably is.
I'm not sure what my name's in that book, but I think it probably is.
Well, would you say that things have changed more here than they have in San Ignacio?
Yes, it has changed more here.
Do you think that's because of moving?
Yes, because of moving, and now we have more people.
We have a lot more people living in this new town now.
And on account of the time, we have more people living and we have more business than now.
Well, thank you very much.
I'm pretty sure he gives you a lot of information, because I know.
Oh, I hope so.
How do you think?
Do you think he's still around?
Well, I don't know.
But he is just about half a block from here.
Well, would it be all right if we just go by his house?
I'm pretty sure.
This is very nice.
Mary, would you get the plug for me?
Mr. San Miguel, could you give me his address?
How might I find it?
Here.
Okay.
Thank you.
